## Addition and Subtraction {#addition_and_subtraction}
1. **Decompose and Recompose Power Series for Sum of Functions:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to decompose functions \( f \) and \( g \) into their respective power series around the same center \( c \) and recompose the power series to represent the sum of the functions. - **Details:** This involves understanding the power series representation of functions, performing termwise addition, and verifying the resulting power series. For example, given \( f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n (x - c)^n \) and \( g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n (x - c)^n \), students will demonstrate \( f(x) + g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (a_n + b_n) (x - c)^n \).
2. **Decompose and Recompose Power Series for Difference of Functions:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to decompose functions \( f \) and \( g \) into their respective power series around the same center \( c \) and recompose the power series to represent the difference of the functions. - **Details:** This involves understanding the power series representation of functions, performing termwise subtraction, and verifying the resulting power series. For example, given \( f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n (x - c)^n \) and \( g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n (x - c)^n \), students will demonstrate \( f(x) - g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (a_n - b_n) (x - c)^n \).
3. **Analyze Radius of Convergence for Combined Power Series:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to analyze the radius of convergence for the combined power series of the sum or difference of functions \( f \) and \( g \) and determine if it changes. - **Details:** This includes examining cases where the radii of convergence of the original power series are the same, and understanding why the radius of convergence of the sum or difference may differ. For example, with \( a_n = (-1)^n \) and \( b_n = (-1)^{n+1} \left(1 - \frac{1}{3^n}\right) \), students will show that although the series for \( f \) and \( g \) have a radius of convergence of 1, the series for \( f(x) + g(x) \) has a radius of convergence of 3.
## Multiplication and Division {#multiplication_and_division}
1. **Calculate the Power Series for Product of Functions:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to calculate the power series for the product of two functions \( f \) and \( g \) given their individual power series representations. - **Details:** This involves understanding the convolution of sequences and performing the necessary calculations. Given \( f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n (x - c)^n \) and \( g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n (x - c)^n \), students will compute \( f(x)g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \left( \sum_{i=0}^n a_i b_{n-i} \right) (x - c)^n \).
2. **Solve for Coefficients in Power Series Division:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to solve for the coefficients of the power series representation of the quotient of two functions \( f \) and \( g \). - **Details:** This involves using the recursive relationship derived from the product of the series. Given \( \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty d_n (x - c)^n \), students will solve for \( d_n \) using the provided determinant formula.
3. **Apply Convolution in Power Series Multiplication:** - **Outcome:** Students will be able to apply the concept of convolution to find the power series representation of the product of two functions. - **Details:** This includes performing the convolution of the sequences of coefficients from the power series of the functions. For instance, students will compute \( m_n = \sum_{i=0}^n a_i b_{n-i} \) to find the coefficients for the power series of \( f(x)g(x) \).
